to court not for the murder of the slaves but as a suit against the insurers who denied the owners' claim that their "cargo" had been necessarily jettisoned. The scandalous case prompted wide debate and fueled Britain's awakening abolition movement. Without the episode of the Zong, Walvin contends, the process of ending the slave trade would have taken an entirely different moral and political trajectory. He concludes with a fascinating discussion of how the case of the Zong, though unique in the history of slave ships, has come to be understood as typical of life on all such ships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAntislavery movementsxHistoryxGreat BritainxGro→britannien. 0aMarine insurancexHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aMass murderxHistoryx18th century. 0aSeafaring lifexHistoryx18th century. 0aSlave tradexHistoryx18th centuryxEnglandxLiverpool. 0aSlave tradexHistoryx18th centuryxJamaica. 0aSlaveryxLaw and legislationxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aSlavesxViolence againstxHistoryx18th century. 0aTrialsxHistoryx18th centuryxEnglandxLondon. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300180756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300180756.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles